## This file is a team contract

`.codecannon.yaml` and the generated `.claude/commands/` files are committed to this repo. Every developer gets a consistent workflow on `git clone` + `git submodule update --init` — no further setup required.

To update skills: `git submodule update --remote CodeCannon && CodeCannon/sync.sh`
To reconfigure: edit `.codecannon.yaml` and re-run `CodeCannon/sync.sh`, then commit the changes.

## Agent Workflow

This project uses **Code Cannon** for agent workflow skills. Skills are available as:

- **Claude Code:** `/start`, `/submit-for-review`, `/review`, `/version`, `/release`, `/status`, `/qa`, `/setup` slash commands
- **Cursor:** `@start`, `@submit-for-review`, etc. in Agent mode

### Quick reference

| Skill | When to use |
|---|---|
| `/start [description]` | Begin a new feature or bugfix |
| `/start [issue-number]` | Resume work on an existing GitHub issue |
| `/submit-for-review` | Type-check, commit, open PR, agent review, merge to integration branch |
| `/review [pr-number]` | Standalone code review |
| `/version` | Bump version, tag, push — run after features are merged to integration branch |
| `/release` | Promote integration branch to main, create GitHub Release, close issues |
| `/status` | Snapshot of your open PRs, recently merged work, and open issues |
| `/status --milestone <name>` | Sprint or milestone progress summary |
| `/qa` | Show issues waiting for QA review |
| `/qa [issue-number]` | Record QA findings and apply verdict label to an issue |
| `/setup` | First-run onboarding and configuration check |

## QA Workflow

> This workflow applies in two-branch mode (BRANCH_DEV is set, BRANCH_TEST is empty). Skip this section if using trunk or three-branch mode.

When `/submit-for-review` merges a feature, it applies the `ready-for-qa` label (or whatever label you've set as `QA_READY_LABEL` in `.codecannon.yaml`) to the linked issue (if configured). This signals the feature is deployed to preview and ready for verification.

To review the QA queue: `/qa`
To record findings on an issue: `/qa <issue-number>`

A human QA reviewer can perform the same steps manually: open the issue, comment with findings, and update the labels. The workflow is the same either way.

## What Agents Must Never Do

- Push directly to any protected branch
- Merge PRs directly to `{{BRANCH_PROD}}` except via `/submit-for-review` (trunk mode) or `/release` (two-branch/three-branch mode)
- Merge PRs directly to `{{BRANCH_TEST}}` — that promotion step is manual or via a future /promote skill
- Run destructive commands (drop DB, clear prod data) without explicit human instruction
- Commit `.env` files, secrets, or build artifacts
- Apply QA verdict labels (`qa-passed`, `qa-failed`) without posting a comment with findings first

